  "prompt": "What is the economic system of Pakistan? How long has this been the system?",
  "response": "Pakistan has a mixed economy that incorporates elements of both capitalism and socialism. The country\u2019s economic system includes a combination of private and public sector enterprises, with significant government involvement in key industries and sectors, such as energy, transportation, and agriculture. \n\nAgriculture has traditionally been a cornerstone of the economy, with a significant portion of the population engaged in farming. The industrial sector has also developed over the years, contributing to manufacturing and exports. Services have become an increasingly important part of the economy, particularly in urban areas.\n\nThe economic system of Pakistan has evolved since its independence in 1947. Initially, the country adopted a more socialist-oriented model in the 1960s under President Ayub Khan, with significant government ownership of industries. However, from the late 1970s onwards, the country shifted towards a more market-oriented approach, especially during the 1980s and 1990s.\n\nSince the early 2000s, Pakistan has continued to implement economic reforms aimed at liberalization, privatization, and deregulation, although the extent and success of these efforts have varied over time.\n\nOverall, the mixed economic system of Pakistan has been in place in various forms since independence, but it has undergone significant changes in structure and implementation over the decades.",
